04633nam a22007095i 9780292769960DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211966txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927699607 a10.7560/7330462doi  a(DE-B1597)587934  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aHG185.M6bB7 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a332.09721 aBrothers, Dwight S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMexican Financial Development /cLeopoldo Solís M., Dwight S. Brothers. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1966  a1 online resource (252 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Tables -- tList of Charts and Diagrams -- tPart I. The Early Stages -- tChapter I. Development of Financial System prior to 1940 -- tPart II. The 1940-1960 Period—History -- tChapter II. Money and Capital Market -- tChapter III. Monetary and Financial Policy -- tChapter IV. Monetary and Financial Experience -- tPart III. The 1940-1960 Period—Analysis -- tChapter V. Internal Stability and External Equilibrium -- tChapter VI. Financial Processes and Economic Growth -- tPart IV. Developments since 1960 -- tChapter VII. Recent Experience and Future Development -- tGuide to Further Reading -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe development of the Mexican financial system as it has related to the remarkable growth of the Mexican economy is examined in this book. Believing that a better understanding of the past will permit a more nearly accurate appraisal of contemporary problems and facilitate the choice of intelligent policies in the future, the authors present a detailed chronicle and analysis of components of the Mexican financial system, with primary emphasis on the period from 1940 to the mid-1960s. Separate chapters are devoted to the money and capital market, the formulation and execution of monetary and financial policies, and the nature of Mexican financial experience in both the public and private sectors of the economy. The authors offer a theoretical explanation of the record of Mexican experience, based upon their analysis of relationships between monetary policy, domestic stability, and external equilibrium, as well as upon their analysis of factors governing the growth of domestic indebtedness, the development of financial intermediation, and the operation of the loanable funds market. The final chapter of the book, a review of Mexican experience from 1960 to 1965, speculates with respect to the future course of Mexican financial development and offers specific proposal for future monetary and financial policies. This record of Mexican financial development contains much that should be of interest to others engaged in related theoretical and empirical studies, including many lessons for those countries confronted with circumstances and problems not too unlike those encountered in Mexico.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aFinancezMexico. 0aFinance--Mexico. 0aMonetary policyzMexico. 0aSaving and investmentzMexico. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aSolís M., Leopoldo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/73304640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292769960423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292769960/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK